Feature flags and interface abstractions act as **seams** that isolate code, enabling safe removal or replacement. 

**Example: Feature Flag**
javascript
// Before: Hardcoded feature
function processOrder(order) {
  if (order.type === 'premium') {
    applyPremiumDiscount(order);
  }
  // ... other logic
}

// After: Feature flag
const isPremiumDiscountEnabled = false; // Can be toggled globally

function processOrder(order) {
  if (isPremiumDiscountEnabled) {
    applyPremiumDiscount(order);
  }
  // ... other logic
}


With the flag, you can **disable the feature in seconds** without modifying core logic. Similarly, replacing an implementation behind an interface (e.g., swapping a `PaymentProcessor` class) requires minimal changes to callers.

**Key Benefit:** These techniques reduce the cost of removal by localizing changes to a single point.
